    page: 4,
    title: "NVIDIA GPU Operator and Device Plugin Deep Dive",
    content: "The NVIDIA GPU Operator is a critical component that bridges the gap between Kubernetes container orchestration and GPU hardware. Without it, Kubernetes has no awareness of GPU resources and cannot schedule GPU workloads. Understanding its architecture and the role of the device plugin is essential for reliable GPU infrastructure.\n\nThe GPU Operator follows the Kubernetes operator pattern: it watches for GPU nodes joining the cluster and automatically installs all required software components on each node. This eliminates the need to bake GPU drivers into custom AMIs or run manual installation scripts on each node. When a new GPU node joins the cluster (whether added manually or by Karpenter's auto-scaling), the GPU Operator detects it, installs the appropriate NVIDIA driver version, and makes the GPU available for workloads within minutes.\n\nThe software stack installed by the GPU Operator includes several layers. At the base is the NVIDIA GPU driver, which provides the kernel-level interface to the GPU hardware. Above that is the NVIDIA Container Toolkit, which enables GPU passthrough into Docker and containerd containers. The CUDA toolkit provides the runtime libraries needed by GPU applications. And at the top is the device plugin, which integrates with the Kubernetes scheduler.\n\nThe device plugin deserves special attention because it is the interface between GPU hardware and Kubernetes scheduling. The Kubernetes device plugin framework allows vendors to advertise custom hardware resources to the scheduler. The NVIDIA device plugin registers GPU resources under the resource name nvidia.com/gpu. Pods can then request GPU resources using the standard resource specification: resources.limits with nvidia.com/gpu set to the number of GPUs required. The scheduler uses this information to place pods only on nodes that have available GPUs.\n\nWhen a pod requests GPU resources, the Kubernetes scheduler finds a node with sufficient available GPUs and assigns the pod to that node. The device plugin on that node allocates specific GPU devices to the pod's containers, sets the NVIDIA_VISIBLE_DEVICES environment variable, and configures the container runtime to provide GPU access. This allocation is exclusive by default: a GPU allocated to one pod is not available to other pods, preventing resource contention.\n\nGPU sharing through Multi-Instance GPU (MIG) or time-slicing is an advanced feature supported by the device plugin. MIG partitions an A100 GPU into up to seven isolated instances, each with dedicated memory and compute resources. Time-slicing allows multiple pods to share a GPU through temporal multiplexing. For inference workloads where each request uses only a fraction of the GPU's capacity, sharing can significantly improve resource utilization.\n\nMonitoring GPU health and utilization requires the NVIDIA DCGM Exporter, which is also installed by the GPU Operator. This component exposes GPU metrics (temperature, memory usage, power draw, utilization, error counts) as Prometheus metrics. These metrics feed into Grafana dashboards for visualization and Prometheus alerts for automated monitoring. GPU temperature exceeding thermal limits, memory errors indicating hardware degradation, and sustained low utilization indicating over-provisioning are all conditions that should trigger alerts.\n\nInstalling the GPU Operator through Terraform uses the Helm provider. The Helm release resource specifies the chart repository, chart name, chart version, namespace, and any custom values. A critical dependency is that the Helm release must wait for the EKS cluster and node groups to be ready before attempting installation. Terraform's implicit dependency resolution handles this when the Helm provider's host and token are derived from the EKS cluster resource outputs.\n\nTroubleshooting GPU Operator issues typically involves checking the operator's pod logs and the status of its custom resources. The ClusterPolicy resource shows the overall status of GPU stack deployment. Node Feature Discovery labels indicate whether nodes have been correctly identified as GPU nodes. The device plugin pod's logs show whether GPUs were successfully registered with the kubelet.",
    key_takeaways: [
      "The GPU Operator automatically installs drivers, container toolkit, CUDA, and device plugins on GPU nodes joining the cluster",
      "The device plugin advertises nvidia.com/gpu resources to the Kubernetes scheduler, enabling GPU-aware pod placement",
      "GPU allocation is exclusive by default; MIG and time-slicing enable sharing for better utilization on inference workloads",
      "DCGM Exporter provides GPU health and utilization metrics for Prometheus/Grafana monitoring"
    ]
