    page: 6,
    title: "Practical Workflow: From Code to Running Cluster",
    content: "Translating the Terraform configurations into a running GPU cluster requires a disciplined workflow that handles initialization, progressive validation, and operational verification. This section walks through the complete practical workflow.\n\nThe starting point is the Terraform directory structure. A well-organized project separates the configuration into logical files: main.tf for the primary resource definitions, variables.tf for input variable declarations, outputs.tf for exported values, providers.tf for provider configuration, and versions.tf for provider version constraints. For larger projects, modules can be separated into subdirectories. The terraform.tfvars file provides default variable values and should be Git-ignored if it contains sensitive information like credentials.\n\nBefore running terraform init, ensure the AWS CLI is configured with appropriate credentials. Terraform uses the AWS provider, which reads credentials from the standard AWS credential chain: environment variables, shared credentials file, or IAM instance profile. For team environments, using an IAM role with narrowly scoped permissions is essential. The role needs permissions for EC2, EKS, VPC, IAM, and Helm operations, but should not have administrative access.\n\nThe terraform init command downloads provider plugins and initializes the backend. For production use, configure a remote backend that stores the state file in S3 with DynamoDB locking. This prevents two team members from running apply simultaneously, which could corrupt the state. The backend configuration is specified in the terraform block of the configuration.\n\nRunning terraform plan produces the execution plan. For a fresh deployment, all resources will show as additions. Review this plan carefully, paying particular attention to the instance types (confirming GPU instances are specified), the networking configuration (confirming private subnets for nodes), and the Helm chart versions (confirming compatible versions of GPU Operator and Karpenter). The plan output includes estimated costs for some resource types.\n\nThe terraform apply command should always be run with the plan output to ensure exactly the planned changes are applied. The initial apply for a full cluster typically takes fifteen to twenty minutes, with the EKS cluster creation being the longest step. Watch the output for errors, particularly around IAM permissions and resource quotas. AWS accounts have default quotas on GPU instances that may need to be increased before provisioning GPU nodes.\n\nAfter apply completes, verify the cluster is functioning. The terraform output command provides the cluster endpoint and authentication details. Configure kubectl using the AWS CLI: aws eks update-kubeconfig with the cluster name and region. Then verify the nodes are registered with kubectl get nodes, confirm GPU resources are available with kubectl describe node and checking for nvidia.com/gpu in the allocatable section, and verify the GPU Operator pods are running with kubectl get pods in the gpu-operator namespace.\n\nThe verification step should include running a GPU test pod. Create a simple pod that runs nvidia-smi, which displays GPU information. If the pod runs successfully and shows the expected GPU model and memory, the entire stack from Terraform through EKS through GPU Operator through device plugin is functioning correctly. If the pod fails, check the GPU Operator status, device plugin logs, and node taints.\n\nWhen the training run is complete and the infrastructure is no longer needed, terraform destroy removes all resources in the reverse order of creation. Before destroying, ensure any training checkpoints or model artifacts have been saved to persistent storage outside the cluster (such as S3). The destroy command takes approximately ten to fifteen minutes and should be verified by checking the AWS console to confirm all resources have been removed.",
    key_takeaways: [
      "Remote state backends with DynamoDB locking are essential for team environments to prevent concurrent state corruption",
      "GPU instance quotas must be verified before provisioning; default AWS quotas may not include GPU instance types",
      "Verification includes checking node registration, GPU resource availability, GPU Operator status, and running a test pod",
      "terraform destroy removes all resources cleanly when infrastructure is no longer needed, preventing unnecessary costs"
    ]
