    page: 7,
    title: "Best Practices: Security, Cost, and Operational Excellence",
    content: "Operating IaC-managed AI infrastructure in production requires attention to security hardening, cost optimization, and operational practices that go beyond the basic Terraform configuration.\n\nSecurity starts with network isolation. The EKS cluster should place worker nodes in private subnets with no direct internet access. Outbound traffic flows through NAT gateways, and inbound traffic is restricted to load balancers in public subnets. Security groups should follow the principle of least privilege: nodes communicate with each other and the API server, but external access is limited to specific ports needed for model serving. The Kubernetes API server endpoint can be configured as private, accessible only from within the VPC, to prevent external API attacks.\n\nIAM roles should use IRSA (IAM Roles for Service Accounts) to provide fine-grained permissions to individual Kubernetes workloads. Rather than giving the entire node group broad permissions, each pod gets exactly the permissions it needs through its service account. The training pods might need S3 access for data and checkpoints. The inference pods might need ECR access for container images. The monitoring pods might need CloudWatch access for log shipping. IRSA prevents any single compromised pod from having excessive AWS permissions.\n\nSecrets management for API keys, database credentials, and model registry tokens should use Kubernetes Secrets backed by AWS Secrets Manager or HashiCorp Vault. Never store secrets in Terraform state or in plain text in configuration files. The External Secrets Operator can automatically synchronize secrets from AWS Secrets Manager into Kubernetes, providing a clean integration between cloud secret management and pod configuration.\n\nCost optimization for GPU workloads requires a multi-layered approach. At the infrastructure level, use spot instances for training and on-demand for inference. At the scheduling level, use Karpenter's consolidation to eliminate idle capacity. At the workload level, implement training checkpointing so spot interruptions do not waste training progress. At the monitoring level, set up cost alerts that notify the team when spending exceeds expected levels.\n\nTagging strategy is essential for cost allocation and resource management. Every Terraform resource should be tagged with consistent metadata: project name, environment (dev, staging, production), team, cost center, and purpose (training, inference, monitoring). These tags enable AWS Cost Explorer to break down spending by project and purpose, revealing exactly how much each training run or inference deployment costs.\n\nState management practices for teams include: storing state in a remote backend with locking, running plan in CI pipelines for every pull request (so reviewers can see the infrastructure changes), protecting the production state with approval gates, and using workspaces or separate state files for different environments. Never share Terraform state files via email or chat; always use the designated backend.\n\nDisaster recovery planning should include: regular backups of the Terraform state file, documentation of manual steps required beyond Terraform (such as DNS configuration or certificate provisioning), runbooks for common failure scenarios, and practiced recovery procedures. The ability to recreate the entire infrastructure from code is one of IaC's greatest strengths, but it only works if the code is complete and the recovery process has been tested.\n\nContinuous integration for Terraform includes automated formatting checks (terraform fmt), validation (terraform validate), security scanning (tools like tfsec or Checkov that detect security misconfigurations), and plan generation on pull requests. Automated apply should be gated behind manual approval for production changes, while development environments can apply automatically on merge to the main branch.",
    key_takeaways: [
      "Network isolation with private subnets and IRSA for pod-level IAM permissions provide defense-in-depth security",
      "Cost optimization combines spot instances, Karpenter consolidation, training checkpointing, and spend monitoring",
      "Consistent resource tagging enables accurate cost allocation and spending analysis by project and purpose",
      "CI pipelines should include format checks, validation, security scanning, and gated plan/apply workflows"
    ]
