    page: 8,
    title: "Quiz Deep Dive: IaC Concepts and AWS Infrastructure (Part 1)",
    content: "This lesson covers twenty quiz questions spanning IaC fundamentals, Terraform operations, AWS GPU infrastructure, and Kubernetes GPU management. Let us examine each question and understand the reasoning behind the correct answers.\n\nQuestion: What is Infrastructure as Code? The correct answer is writing code to define and manage infrastructure. IaC replaces manual console operations with declarative configuration files. This is not about infrastructure documentation or monitoring but about actual provisioning and lifecycle management through code.\n\nQuestion: Which tool is commonly used for IaC with AWS? The correct answer is Terraform. While AWS has its own CloudFormation service, Terraform is the industry standard multi-cloud IaC tool. Ansible, Chef, and Puppet are configuration management tools rather than infrastructure provisioning tools.\n\nQuestion: What does the NVIDIA GPU Operator do on Kubernetes? The correct answer is it manages GPU drivers and exposes GPU resources to pods. The GPU Operator automates driver installation, container toolkit setup, and device plugin deployment. It does not manage CPU resources, networking, or storage.\n\nQuestion: What is the purpose of Karpenter? The correct answer is to dynamically scale Kubernetes nodes based on workload. Karpenter provisions and terminates nodes in response to pending pod requirements. It replaces or supplements the Cluster Autoscaler with faster, more flexible scaling.\n\nQuestion: Which instance type is commonly used for GPU workloads on AWS? The correct answer is g4dn.xlarge. This instance provides a single T4 GPU and is the most cost-effective option for development, testing, and light inference. The t3 and m5 families do not include GPUs.\n\nQuestion: What does the capacity_type SPOT setting do? The correct answer is it uses spot instances which are cheaper but can be interrupted. Spot instances use spare AWS capacity at significant discounts. The tradeoff is that AWS can reclaim the instance with two minutes notice when capacity is needed.\n\nQuestion: Which command applies the Terraform configuration? The correct answer is terraform apply. This command reads the configuration, computes the diff against current state, and provisions or modifies resources. It is not terraform run or terraform deploy.\n\nQuestion: What does terraform plan do? The correct answer is it shows the changes that will be applied. Plan is the safety preview phase that lets you review additions, modifications, and deletions before they execute. It makes no actual changes.\n\nQuestion: What is the role of the VPC module in the Terraform script? The correct answer is it creates a virtual private cloud for networking. The VPC provides the network isolation and subnet structure within which the Kubernetes cluster operates.\n\nQuestion: Which Kubernetes resource is used to limit GPU usage in a pod? The correct answer is resources.limits with nvidia.com/gpu. This standard Kubernetes resource specification tells the scheduler and device plugin how many GPUs the pod requires.",
    key_takeaways: [
      "IaC replaces manual console operations with version-controlled code for reproducible infrastructure provisioning",
      "Terraform is the multi-cloud standard; Karpenter provides dynamic GPU node scaling; GPU Operator manages the NVIDIA software stack",
      "Spot instances offer significant cost savings for interruptible workloads; g4dn.xlarge is the standard entry-level GPU instance",
      "The terraform plan command provides a safety preview of changes before any infrastructure modification occurs"
    ]
