    content: "This lesson has covered the complete framework for orchestrating ML workflows and versioning training data, forming the operational backbone of a production ML platform for drone AI systems.\n\nKubeflow Pipelines provides the orchestration layer that automates multi-step ML workflows on Kubernetes. Pipelines are defined as Python functions, compiled to YAML workflow specifications, and executed as containerized steps on the Kubernetes cluster. The system handles dependency resolution, resource allocation, step monitoring, and artifact management. The UI provides visibility into run status, step logs, and metric comparison across experiments.\n\nDVC provides the data versioning layer that extends Git to handle large datasets and model files. Through its pointer-file architecture, DVC keeps Git operations fast while providing full version control for arbitrarily large data. Remote storage synchronization through dvc push and dvc pull ensures data is available to all team members and pipeline runs. Git tags on DVC pointer files create named dataset versions.\n\nThe combination of orchestration and versioning creates model lineage: the ability to trace any model artifact back to the exact data, code, and configuration that produced it. This lineage is essential for debugging model degradation, complying with regulatory requirements, and reproducing results. It is implemented through metadata propagation: each pipeline step records its inputs and outputs, creating an auditable chain from raw data to deployed model.\n\nAdvanced patterns including step caching, parallel execution, conditional logic, and multi-stage promotion create efficient, flexible pipelines that handle the complexity of production ML operations. Operational considerations around artifact storage, compute management, monitoring, and troubleshooting ensure the pipeline infrastructure itself remains reliable.\n\nTo assess your understanding, consider these self-check questions. Can you describe the complete lifecycle of data through DVC: from initial tracking through versioning to retrieval in a pipeline? Can you design a Kubeflow pipeline with appropriate components for a drone model training workflow? Can you explain how model lineage connects a production model to its training data? Can you identify and resolve common failure patterns in ML pipelines?\n\nThis lesson builds on the IaC foundations from the previous lesson (the Kubernetes infrastructure runs Kubeflow) and connects forward to model serving and CI/CD, where the orchestrated pipeline's outputs are deployed and continuously validated.",
